><div class="flex min-w-0 flex-1 flex-col justify-start gap-2"><div class="flex flex-row flex-wrap items-center gap-2"><div class="flex-0 mask relative aspect-square h-8 w-8 lg:hidden inline-block"><img src="https://staging.cohostcdn.org/avatar/28756-c3d86492-d925-4672-9542-7a334b9c5d09-profile.png?dpr=2&amp;width=80&amp;height=80&amp;fit=cover&amp;auto=webp" class="mask mask-roundrect h-full w-full object-cover" alt="AlexStemcell"/></div><a rel="author" href="https://cohost.org/AlexStemcell" class="co-project-display-name max-w-full flex-shrink truncate font-atkinson font-bold hover:underline" title="🏳️‍🌈 Alex Stemcell">🏳️‍🌈 Alex Stemcell</a><a href="https://cohost.org/AlexStemcell" class="co-project-handle font-atkinson font-normal hover:underline">@<!-- -->AlexStemcell<!-- --></a><time dateTime="2023-01-23T23:15:14.103Z" class="block flex-none text-xs tabular-nums text-gray-500" title="Mon, Jan 23, 2023, 11:15 PM"><a href="#comment-557065cc-7007-491b-abd1-86374c782a3e" class="hover:underline">1/23/2023, 11:15 PM</a></time></div><div class="co-prose prose overflow-hidden break-words"><p>Fun fact: The Sega Genesis/Mega Drive can shear background layers horizontally on a scanline-by-scanline basis, are vertically in 2-tile-wide blocks, and several games used this to simulate limited rotation (because at shallow angles, the visual elongation caused by not doing the third shear isn&#x27;t as noticeable), notably Streets of Rage 2 and Castlevania: Bloodline.<!-- --></p>
